<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="140">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="140">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="140">Distribution</pageStartToken>
</pageStartToken>
. Locally common throughout Denmark and Fennoscandia, not found in British Isles. - Range: Jura Alps to North Japan, Italy to North Norway.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="140">
Biology. This species has large spreading colonies among stones or in tree stumps with loose surface leaf litter sometimes built into a shallow loose mound. This is an aggressive acid squirting species found at the borders of woodland and in stony banks and often particularly abundant on offshore islands. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29231" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" genus.bestMatchDistance="68" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica truncorum Fabricius" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="truncorum">F. truncorum</taxonomicName>
is normally polygynous, sometimes with many small dark headed queens. New colonies may be formed by nest splitting or by the adoption of single large red headed queens by 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29086" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" genus.bestMatchDistance="725" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica fusca Linnaeus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">F. fusca</taxonomicName>
and allied species. Males and queens occur in July and August, latter than with most members of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29198" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" genus.bestMatchDistance="26" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica rufa Linnaeus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufa">F. rufa</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
